        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p>Never published before <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>117800</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <div type="textpart" n="a">
                    <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Φι_"><abbr>Φι</abbr></name></persName>
                    </ab>
                </div>
                <div type="textpart" n="b">
                    <ab>
                        <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Σω_"><abbr>Σω</abbr></name></persName>
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p/>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Intraduisible.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Not usefully translatable.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Intraducibile.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
            <p>غير قابل للترجمة بشكل جيد</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
	   <p>Abbreviated names are common in such ephebic graffiti; there exist many names beginning with <foreign xml:lang="grc">Φι</foreign> and 
	  <foreign xml:lang="grc">Σω</foreign>, so that no restoration of names originally written in full nor expansion of abbreviation can be proposed.</p>
            </div></body>
